text:
No wonder the poet said:
Living, He loved me; dying, He saved me;
Buried, He carried my sins far away;
Rising, He justified freely forever;
Someday He's coming, O glorious day!"
Was a God-Man! God was in His Son, reconciling the world to Himself. They had claimed Him to be a magician, and a soothsayer, and a devil, and Beelzebub, and everything. But He was God Immanuel, dwelling among us, reconciling the world to Himself. (We got that on a question in the morning, anyhow; we'll get on that and finish that tomorrow.) All right.

text_no:
Ikke rart at poeten sa:
"Levende elsket Han meg; døende frelste Han meg;
Begravet bar Han mine synder langt bort;
Oppstått rettferdiggjorde Han meg fritt for alltid;
En dag kommer Han igjen, å herlige dag!"
Han var en Gud-mann! Gud var i Sin Sønn, og forlikte verden med Seg Selv. De hadde kalt Ham en magiker, en spåmann, en djevel, og Beelzebub, og alt mulig. Men Han var Gud Immanuel, som bodde blant oss, og forlikte verden med Seg Selv. (Vi fikk det på et spørsmål i morges; vi skal gå gjennom det og avslutte det i morgen.) Greit.
